3. Statistical Test Questions
3A. 4-Mark Version (No Context Required)
Structure:

Identification (1 mark): State the name of the test
Justification 1 — Test type (1 mark): Is the researcher looking for a difference or a correlation/association?
Justification 2 — Design (1 mark): Is it independent groups (unrelated) or repeated measures/matched pairs (related)? OR is it a correlational design?
Justification 3 — Data type (1 mark): Is the data nominal (categories), ordinal (ordered/ranked/rating scales), or interval/ratio (measurable with equal intervals)?
Model Answer:

A psychology teacher conducted an independent groups experiment with 30 students using a happiness questionnaire.

Answer:

The most appropriate test is the Mann-Whitney U test.

This is because:

The teacher is looking for a difference (between the two groups' happiness scores)
It is an independent groups design (different participants in each group)
She collected ordinal data (happiness questionnaire produces ranked/ordered data)
3B. 7-Mark Version (With Context Required)
Structure:

Identification (1 mark): Name the statistical test
Justification 1 + Context (2 marks): State whether looking for difference/correlation AND link explicitly to the study
Justification 2 + Context (2 marks): State the design AND explain why using study details
Justification 3 + Context (2 marks): State the data type AND explain why using study details
Each justification = 1 mark for the reason + 1 mark for applying to the scenario. You MUST contextualise each point.

Model Answer:

A psychologist tested the effects of recreational screen time on children's academic performance. 58 pupils randomly allocated to Group A (no screen time) or Group B (unrestricted screen time). All completed a 45-minute class test.

Answer:

The most appropriate test is the Mann-Whitney U test.

This is because:

The teacher is looking for a difference — specifically, between no recreational screen time and unlimited recreational screen time on exam performance
It is an independent groups design — as the pupils either had no recreational screen time OR unlimited recreational screen time (they were in one group only)
She collected ordinal data — as the difference between each test score is not fixed (test scores from a class test are ranked/ordered data)
Examiner Commentary:

This receives full marks (7/7) as the statistical test is correctly identified for 1 mark along with three correct justifications for 3 marks. Each justification is explicitly linked to the study and therefore receives a further 3 marks.

4. Critical Value / Significance Table Questions
Structure (4 marks):

Identify the critical value (1 mark): State the exact number from the table
Justify — One-tailed or two-tailed (1 mark): Is the hypothesis directional (one-tailed) or non-directional (two-tailed)?
Justify — N or df value (1 mark): State the number of participants / degrees of freedom
Justify — Significance level (1 mark): State the p-value (e.g., 0.05)
Key Rules for Reading Tables:

Check whether calculated value must be ≥ critical value (Spearman's, Pearson's, Chi-squared) or ≤ critical value (Mann-Whitney, Wilcoxon, Sign test) to be significant
One-tailed = directional hypothesis (predicts a specific direction)
Two-tailed = non-directional hypothesis (predicts a difference/correlation but not direction)
Model Answer:

A researcher hypothesised a positive correlation between hours slept and feeling rested. N = 18, one-tailed, p ≤ 0.05. Calculated rho = 0.395. The critical value for rho must be ≥ calculated value.

Answer:

The critical value is 0.401.

This is because:

The hypothesis is directional (positive correlation), so it is a one-tailed test
There are 18 participants, so N = 18
The level of significance is 0.05 (5%)
Since the calculated value (0.395) is less than the critical value (0.401), the result is not significant and we must retain the null hypothesis.

