Model Answer:

Ellis proposed an ABC model of depression. Outline and evaluate the ABC model of depression. Refer to this diary extract in your answer. [8 marks]

Diary: "Managed to drag myself out of the house yesterday but wished I hadn't. Went to the shop but dropped my change at the till. Everybody knew I was useless. Why can I not do anything right? No one else I know does such stupid things."

The ABC model explains how irrational thoughts affect our behaviour and emotions. Ellis (1962) argued that depression is caused by irrational thoughts, which are triggered by negative external events. This is known as the activating event (A).

An event, such as failing an important test, may trigger irrational beliefs (B) such as "I must always succeed"; Ellis called this musturbation. As a result, there are emotional and behavioural consequences (C), such as low self-esteem and social withdrawal, i.e., depression symptoms.

In the diary entry above, the activating event was the individual dropping change at the till. This triggered irrational beliefs such as "they all knew I was useless" and "no one else does such stupid things." The emotional and behavioural consequences of these beliefs are a continued cycle of depression whereby the individual may never leave the house again.

A strength of Ellis' ABC model of depression is that it has practical applications as it has led to successful therapy, i.e., REBT. The idea that, by identifying and disputing irrational beliefs, a person can reduce their depression is supported by research evidence, such as Lipskey et al. (1980), who found a correlation between changes in beliefs and changes in emotional distress. This in turn supports the basic theory because it suggests that the irrational beliefs played a role in the development of depression.

(225 words — Level 4: 7–8 marks)

Examiner Commentary:

Top band. Detailed AO1 with key terms. Application is effective — diary content is linked to theory (not just quoted). Evaluation elaborated with research findings and linked back.

Critical Rule for AO2 Application:

Do NOT just repeat the stem. You must create an explanatory link — explain WHY the behaviour/situation in the stem fits the theory. E.g., "The activating event was dropping change at the till, which triggered the irrational belief that 'everybody knew I was useless,' demonstrating Ellis's concept of musturbation."

7. 12-Mark Research Design Questions
Mark Split: Varies — typically all three AOs tested

Structure: Answer EVERY bullet point in the question. Use subheadings matching the question prompts.

Common Prompts & What to Include:

Prompt	What to Write
Task for participants	Describe the specific task, duration, instructions given, how standardisation is ensured
Behavioural categories & recording	List specific observable behaviours, describe the recording method (tally chart, behaviour checklist), state sampling method (event/time sampling)
Reliability	Describe inter-observer reliability — two observers independently record, correlate their tallies, +0.8 = high reliability
Ethical issues	Informed consent (consent form with details), right to withdraw (at any time, no penalty), confidentiality (data anonymised), debrief
Sampling method	Describe how and why (e.g., opportunity, random, volunteer)
Variables	Identify IV, DV, and how they are operationalised
Controls	Describe standardised procedures, extraneous variables, demand characteristics
Model Answer:

Design an observation study to investigate sex differences in non-verbal behaviour when giving a presentation. [12 marks]

Task for participants:

Ask participants to give a presentation to 10 audience members on a hobby they participate in
They will plan and deliver a 5-minute presentation called "My Hobby"
They can only use hand-held prompt cards
All given the same instructions delivered in the same way to ensure standardisation
Behavioural categories and recording:

Categories: making eye contact with audience, looking away from audience, speech hesitations, arms folded, smiling, touching face/hair
Recorded on a behaviour checklist drawn up beforehand by at least 2 observers
Event sampling used — tallying non-verbal behaviours throughout each 5-minute presentation
Reliability:

Prior to research, two observers agree on specific behavioural categories and method of categorising so subjective interpretation is not possible
Both observe each participant independently, then correlate their tallies
A correlation of +0.8 or above indicates high inter-observer reliability
Ethical issues:

Informed consent obtained before the study via a consent form detailing the aim, procedure, participant's role, and duration
Participants informed of their right to withdraw themselves and their data at any time
Reassurance that details will be kept confidential
(314 words — Level 4: 10–12 marks)

Examiner Commentary:

Top band. Clear, practical, well-justified design. Effective use of key terms (e.g., inter-rater reliability). Logical structure addressing all four elements.

