Model Answer:

Outline and evaluate research into two factors affecting the accuracy of eyewitness testimony. [16 marks]

Paragraph 1 (AO1): Leading questions' impact on EWT accuracy was examined by Loftus & Palmer (1974). After showing film clips of car accidents to American students, they questioned them about the incident. Participants were asked to describe how fast the cars were going when they "hit" each other. The verb "hit" implies speed, making this a leading question. Each of the five groups received a distinct verb: contacted, bumped, collided, or smashed.

Paragraph 2 (AO1): For every group, the mean estimated speed was calculated. For "contacted," the mean was 31.8 mph; for "smashed," the mean was 40.5 mph. The findings demonstrate that leading questions have an impact on EWT accuracy.

Paragraph 3 (AO1): Post-event discussion is another factor. Gabbert et al. (2003) found that 71% of participants misrecalled details they had heard during discussion but had not seen in the video. This shows how conversations among co-witnesses can taint EWTs.

Paragraph 4 (AO3): A limitation of Loftus & Palmer is that participants watched film clips, not real accidents. Since clips lack the stress of actual events, this lacks ecological validity and may not reflect how leading questions influence EWT in real criminal cases. Given real-life consequences, EWT may be more reliable than studies indicate.

Paragraph 5 (AO3): Individual differences are a further limitation. Anastasi & Rhodes (2006) found 18–25 and 35–45 age groups were more accurate than the 55–78 group. Because Loftus & Palmer used university students, their findings lack population validity and cannot easily be generalised to other age groups.

Paragraph 6 (AO3): On the other hand, the study has significant real-world implications. Mistaken eyewitness identification is the biggest factor leading to conviction of innocent people (Wells & Olson, 2003). Loftus (1975) argues officers should be careful how they phrase questions. This demonstrates how the work can prevent miscarriages of justice.

(486 words — Level 4: 13–16 marks)

Examiner Commentary:

Top band. Detailed AO1 with two factors and relevant studies. Selective and focused. Evaluation is effective — each point introduced, elaborated with contextualised criticism (not generic), and linked back to the question.

Paragraph-by-Paragraph Breakdown:

